I want to do this to help support the amazing work of Macmillan cancer support because they have helped to support so many people that I hold close to my heart. Over my life I have seen them supporting a number of people and I know first hand the difference they can make for those living with cancer. They provide an invaluable service to those suffering and their families. Macmillan is the most incredible charity, a charity that puts compassion and care before anything else. Jack x

charity.description:
The nation’s leading first aid charity.
Every year, more than 400,000 people learn how to save a life through our training programmes.
Our volunteers provide first aid in their communities and thanks to them fewer lives will be lost needlessly. 
Raise money. Help save lives. Be the difference.
charity.name: St John Ambulance
story:
Help us to raise money for St John Ambulance

Can you help us raise money for an amazing charity that helps save people's lives?

St John Ambulance is the charity that steps forward in the moments that matter to save lives and keep communities safe. They provide first aid services from the community to emergency support. They have supported the NHS during the covid-19 pandemic and they provide training to companies and authorities and also members of the public (Including myself having recently joined the St John's cadets)

I joined St John Ambulance cadets to help make a positive impact and to help people. My interest started when we were coming back from visiting my Grandad and then I saw a St John Ambulance. I questioned what it was and my dad told me it was a St John Ambulance. This is when we discovered that they do cadet training.I thought, "sign me up!

All of St John Ambulance's charitable work is entirely funded by donations which is why we have decided to plan an event and raise money that will contribute to help support communities and help save people's lives. 


When I put the cadet uniform on I will help make a difference. Can you help me make that difference?


As a charity with a long history of serving humanity, we are proud of our past, our role in the pandemic and excited about creating a healthier, safer, brighter and more resilient future.This winter may be our toughest yet and I am helping to bring some community spirit by sharing my sparkle by supporting St John. St John volunteers treat and transport thousands of patients each year, and in times of crisis we are England's national health reserve. During the pandemic our skilled and highly trained volunteers are working long shifts supporting sick people and their families, in hospitals, in ambulances and at home. We are proud to be working alongside the nations ambulance trusts and in hospitals around the country."I enjoy helping people and its what I have been training to do. Its very rewarding personally knowing that my colleagues and I are making a difference to peoples lives when they most need it." Tom Willis, volunteer Will you support me and help make a difference?

Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting our fundraising page. 

So in a Bud fuelled moment of total madness Jacky came up with the hairbrained idea that we could do a virtual LandsEnd to John O Groats Challenge & for some silly reason ( must be the thought of turning 50!! ) I agreed ... Now we've had some silly ideas before but usually they involve sliding downstairs on a pillow after to many cocktails, but this one we will mainly be doing sober! 

So along with our Creaky Knees dodgy hips & otherwise dilapidated bodies we decided to make it worth the challenge & thought we could do this for a worthy
cause & one very close to my heart after losing my Dad.

So after you've stopped laughing maybe you could Sponsor us ?

Our aim is to complete the 1083miles by the end of the year ....

We are  raising money for the British Heart Foundation and wed be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks so much.

Love Mel & Jacky 💜💕 Xxx

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Am so proud that Amelie is joining me in the de-chox this year! Not sure she realises how tough it will be! WHAT? Not even the choc flavour puddings at school? NO!

I LOVE chocolate and eat far too much of it but I will do this for my mum, a former chocoholic! No cocoa in any form will pass our lips!  We will also go crisp and alcohol free too! 

We are doing it because the BHF need to make breakthroughs in the genetic conditions that take our loved ones away so suddenly. Our family  have 50/50 chance of having this gene but there's so much to learn about it. So we need as much money as we can gather. 

Please give what you can. Every pound helps.

Wish us luck!

Kirsty and Amelie xx

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: The British Heart Foundation turns 60 this year and we wanted to mark the occasion. With support from Luton Town Football Club Community Trust the challenge is to walk/run/cycle the equivalent of 60 miles (100K) during the month of March (31 days) which is equates to roughly 2miles/3K per day. This is aimed at getting everyone in Luton moving following lockdown, improving their health and wellbeing. If we could get 100 people signed up to each raise just £60, Luton could raise an amazing £6,000 to fund our life saving research and help those 68,000 people in Bedfordshire living with Heart and Circulatory diseases. Please use the hashtag #HATTERS100K in any social media posts to hopefully create some noise in the Town about our challenge.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
From My Heart...

If you know me well, you know how much I love chocolate and I also enjoy helping people and joining good causes. I have decided then to be part of the Dechox Challange and raise money to keep supporting the BHF research and make possible more hearts beating, specially those little ones... 

I’ll add £1 for every chocolate I would like to eat this month (so far I have added £10 and it’s only the first days of the month...)

To The British Heart Foundation...

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting our page. 

It’s that DECHOX time of year again ❤️ And once again Paige (and her Best Friend Brooke 💕) is joining me in giving up chocolate for the whole of March 😊        Heart conditions are something that has affected our family in one way or another more than anything else, so the British Heart Foundation is a charity close to our heart ❤️(Pun intended 😉).

The pandemic is the biggest challenge the BHF has faced in a 60 year history and had led to a devastating decision to cut their 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, they’ve never needed people like us more.

So we are raising money for the British Heart Foundation's research and will be so grateful for your support, that’s why we need your help, no matter how small EVERY penny counts!! 

Let's help save a heart ❤️

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story: The sad passing of one of our colleagues has been a shock to us all and may of made us all realise how short life can be. Due to the nature of Sean‘s passing and the support Sean’s family want to provide for the British Heart Foundation the team have decided at MIA Train Station to walk 12,500 steps a day throughout the whole march to raise funds for this worth while cause. Anyone is welcome to join in and support us and we thank you all for your donations and support.

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Hi Everyone, 

My Dad Henry was a wonderful man who lost his strong and courageous battle with COVID-19 on 28th February. He was admitted to ICU and spent 7 days fighting so hard to come home to his family. The nurses and doctors told us he was the most cooperative patient who tried his best to fight the virus but he had to be ventilated and his heart became too weak. 

He was a much loved Husband, Dad, Grandad, Uncle, Brother and Friend. He really did light up a room with his big smile, sense of humour and personality. We have had hundreds of people paying tribute to the amazing man he was. It is clear to see he touched the hearts of so many and he will be missed so much. 

Instead of flowers we would like to ask for people to make donations to the British Heart Foundation a charity my Dad always supported. 

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

We love you Chris.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
eventName: 5 miles a day for the month of March
story:
I now know there is a 50% chance I may have this hereditary condition. I have decided along with my new fitness regime, I would like to show my support for the leading heart charity in the UK, as they have already been amazing and offered so much support and guidance!

This is also a good way for me to stay focused on getting fitter and losing weight!

I will be documenting my miles on my social media accounts including my strava account. 

Please give what you can ❤️

**The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks, Ed
title: Edward 's 5 miles a day for the month of March

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
We as a group of friends are jointly raising funds for BHF by participating in a sweet toothed detox challenge! This includes giving up chocolate, fizzy drinks, crisps and sweets for the month of March!

We are doing this in memory of our loved ones who we lost to heart disease. Suki sadly lost both her parents to heart related illnesses both at a young age. Farhana also lost her dad who died of a heart attack at the age of 41, we all know someone who has been affected by heart related illnesses, these funds will contribute towards vital research to help prevent families suffering immeasurable loss and providing ongoing support to families in need

Our family and friends who knows us, will know this is an extremely  tough challenge for each one of us!!  particularly in lockdown, where we have snacked daily on these treats! Any donation big or small is gratefully appreciated  🙏

story:
In March 2021, I will be running & cycling a marathon distance of 26.2 miles to raise money for the British Heart Foundation. My fundraising efforts will go towards my Junior Award Scheme for Schools, JASS. I'd be so grateful for your support and would really appreciate it if you could donate some money towards my chosen charity, the British Heart Foundation. 

To help motivate me on my challenge I’ve linked up to a virtual event, racing along the Inca Trail. I’ll be able to map my progress along this route and to learn about the wonders of Machu Picchu as I go! I can't wait to share my journey with you here.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
eventName: Walk, run or cycle the distance of Lands End to John O’Groats
story:
Thank you for visiting our Just Giving page. For the month of March, we have decided to challenge ourselves as a team, we will walk, run or cycle the distance of Lands End to John O’Groats which is a total of 874 miles. We are completing this distance virtually. We are a team of 6 and will be completing 146 miles each.

This Just Giving page is for the British Heart Foundation. It is a charity very close to my heart as many of my close family members have suffered with heart problems and are still suffering and in these difficult times, we could do our bit for this fantastic cause. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist.We understand that things are difficult for everyone at the moment but any donation will make a difference, even if it’s a £1.

As a team, we work for a company that will match our fundraising up to £500, so your kind donations will be doubled. 

Thank you in advance and we appreciate any encouraging words to help us to go for a walk, run or cycle to get those miles in.

story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation's research and I'd be so grateful for your support as I endeavour to complete the 100km walk at the Peak District Ultra Challenge 2021. Heart disease has always been near and dear to my "heart" ever since I learned of my own issues with high blood pressure in my early 20s. And then over a year ago, my father underwent a heart transplant due to a debilitating disease.  

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound/dollar/euro helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. I hope you can support me either through donations and/or your encouragement! Thanks so much!

story:
Guide Dogs website shows a little girl called Nell who has benefited from this charity and I really want to help them.

Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

story:
Thank you for pledging your support to Pete and Kevs Birthday  challenge for 2021. On the 17th of May I will turn 72 and on the 7th of April Kev will turn 60. We are asking instead of gifts and cards this year you consider donating to our Guide Dogs challenge. We will be talking a small team of family and friends from Brownsover (Rugby) to Draycote water (Dunchurch) which is around a 15 mile walk. The charity is very close to our hearts and we have supported them for many years due to the life changing support they have given our family. The walk will take place on the Sunday 2nd of May.  

The sponsorship money you raise will truly make a difference. £140 could buy a Starter Kit for a new guide dog owner, containing everything they need to start a life with their new guide dog, this includes the iconic white harness. Its thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services, like our guide dogs, to people with sight loss. So, a huge thank you!

If you would like to take part in our walk feel free to message one of us on facebook and we will arrange that.

story:
The sponsored walk thats good for the sole.

Your small steps will help Guide Dogs make giant leaps. Just one week of stepping can make a difference to the life of children and adults living with sight loss. Raise over £50 (£25 for children) and well replace those worn out socks with a brand-new Guide Dogs pair designed by an international fashion icon!

How your funds will change lives...

-	£50 could pay for fun, tactile activities to help children co-ordinate their muscles and movements.

-	£96 could pay for an eye test each for two guide dogs in training

-	£116 could buy a Training School Kit for one of our guide dog trainers who will teach pups the specialist skills they need as fully qualified guide dogs.

-	£710 could buy a Birthing Kit containing all the essential equipment for a guide dog mum to safely deliver her puppies.

Its thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!

story: Welcome to the Amplify Marketing Team Just Giving page. At Amplify, we are committed to giving back to our community and raising money for the causes that matter most. In 2021, we continue to challenge ourselves, and strive to support charities that need our help. In turn, our team is taking the plunge and skydiving to save lives. In May, 14 brave team members will take part in a 12,000 feet tandem skydive to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). GOSH is an international centre of excellence in child healthcare. The hospital receives almost 238,000 outpatient and more than 43,000 inpatient visits every year, and offers the UK’s widest range of specialist health services for children on one site; as well as leading the way in research and development. Please help our team raise a grand total of £5,530 by donating whatever you can today. We thank you in advance for your support and look forward to sharing our fundraising journey with you!

story:
I am running the marathon for GOSH because its an incredible institution and a truly worthy cause. 

Our son Eddie was born with an abdominal legion which was diagnosed as a suspected Neuroblastoma. We were referred to GOSH when he was 8 weeks old, and to this day Eddie continues to be seen regularly there. 

Throughout our experience there we have been in awe of the standard of care at GOSH and moved by how they go the extra mile for the children they look after to try and help them forget their often difficult situations.

We are truly grateful that, so far, Eddie's suspected condition has not worsened and we continue to watch and wait. 

I want to raise money to help GOSH in its incredible work so it can help other people in our situation.

eventName: We are raising funds for Marie Curie through My Peak Challenge 2021
story:
Kirsty's dad Les, died last August from bowel cancer. He was cared for by Marie Curie in his final months and Kirsty said, the hospice gave us our dad back.

When dad was first diagnosed, I felt like my insides had been ripped out, it was a real gut-wrenching moment. He was a single parent and brought us up on his own, so we were all really close. Dad was a really active, sociable man and never viewed himself as an elderly person. When Marie Curie was first mentioned dad wasn't keen and I must admit I also thought that's where you go to die. But he was there for about four weeks and I can honestly say Marie Curie gave us our dad back. That was just the best thing ever - he had no distress and we knew they were taking such good care of him.
The nurses said they would let me know when they felt dad was close to the end so I could stay with him and I ended up self-isolating with him at the hospice for the last week of his life. That meant the world to me. I feel very privileged that I had

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Hey Everyone 

So as most people know every year alongside my family I hold a charity event in aid of Marie Curie or Cancer research. The past few years this has been a ladies afternoon tea.. the last being the week before lockdown hit last March 2020. 

Given we are still in some form of lockdown I didn’t want to give up on my fundraising efforts so I have decided to take on the St Francis Way Virtual Challenge. This will take me 312 miles (503 km) through an ancient Roman road from Florence to the Vatican, following in the footsteps of Saint Francis across the peaceful Italian countryside.. (on my phone lol).

It will certainly be a challenge for myself given my fibromyalgia as there are days walking is painful itself but I am hoping this will also give me a focus whilst raising money for a good cause. My target of £500 may be ambitious but it’s a third of what we normally reach on a ladies afternoon tea day so I am hopeful it’s achievable! 

This is by no means going to be a sprint but a marathon and routine of small steps that is realistic for myself.. for that I am not setting a target other than by the end of 2021.. but I will get there in the end! 

Wish me luck Guys, I will keep you posted with updates and photos if I dare!..  If you can spare a few pennies it would be greatly appreciated 😊

charity.name: Marie Curie
story: In November 2020 I lost my Dad after a short battle with cancer. My Dad chose not to go to hospital so thankfully myself and my sisters got to spend his last days with him at home, which we wouldn't have if he'd have gone to hospital due to COVID-19. During the night, a Marie Curie nurse came to the flat and in a moment she brightened the mood completely; she made us feel at ease, made us smile and laugh, and made my Dad as comfortable as possible before his passing. I wish I'd have said thank you more times than I did, and I wish I could have given her a massive hug for all of her help! I am going to walk 10,000 steps a day through March in memory of my Dad, but also to say a massive thanks to all that Marie Curie nurses do. It would have been his 68th birthday on 6th March 2021 this would be the best birthday present!

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
My best friend and I have taken on the challenge of walking the equivalent of the length of the UK (the route is 1744.2km) for our chosen charities. The challenge will encourage us to be more active for our own mental and physical well-being during lockdown and beyond as well as raising awareness and funds for charities unable to partake in all of their usual fundraising activities due to the current pandemic.

I chose the Marie Curie to support the amazing hospice staff across the UK, including my own mum’s team in the Edinburgh hospice who have worked so hard on the frontline to give the best care and end of life experience possible to every one of the patients that come through their doors.

We will be posting updates and milestones we meet on Facebook during this journey so feel free to take it with us in spirit and support us there. And if you can, please donate anything you’re able to help us out!

Thank you!!!

Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
It is with great sadness we announce the passing of Tom, who sadly lost his fight to a brain tumour on 23rd February aged 38 years.

Amazing adored son of Sue and Tom (Grumpy), the best brother to Gaz, Richard, and Sophie and the late Kai and a treasured nephew, uncle and friend to so many.
A celebration of Tom’s life will be held at York Cemetery Chapel on Monday 15th March at 2.30pm. Due to current restrictions attendance is strictly invitation only. Enquiries to Darley Funeral Directors, Huntington tel: 01904 622746.

This page has been setup with heartfelt thanks to Marie Curie for their love, care and friendship to Tom over the last few weeks. We’d love to raise as much as possible in support of these amazing people and the care they give to their patients and families at a time when it is needed so much.
title: In loving memory of Thomas James Pickering
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Tom Pickering
Name: In loving memory of Thomas James Pickering

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

We have all been touched in some way, by someone needing end of life care, whether its immediate or extended family or friends. Marie Curie offer an amazing service for terminally ill patients.

Maire Curie is the UK's leading end of life charity. They provide front line nursing and hospice care, a free support line and wealth of information and support on all aspects of dying, death and bereavement. 

We wanted to set ourselves a challenge and when we saw the Marie Curie ad to fundraise we thought it could be a great opportunity to raise some money at the same time. So..... call us mad but we have agreed to do 3,000 squats across March, we are doing 100 per day with 1 day grace where we can have a break perhaps if we are too sore....!  It would be great to have your support to keep us going and to raise some funds. 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

We have decided to raise money for Marie Curie in memory of our lovely...here goes - great great Nan, great Nan, Nan, Mum, Mum in law, step Mum and all round bloody wonderful human...wow that woman had more titles than royalty! She always spoke so highly of the support she received all those years ago when she lost Ern, my step Grandad, to lung cancer. She didn't want flowers, cards or to even be scattered after her cremation so we thought this would be a nice tribute instead. She was loved by everyone she met and rightly so, she will be missed so very much but my goodness were we lucky enough that she was ours ❤

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
The David Goggins challenge involves running 4miles every 4hours for 48hours. I blindly agreed to this when suggested by my good friend Tom Bryan (who I will be doing this with whilst also maintaining a safe 65miles social distancing) based on the idea neither of us had really done anything in these lockdowns. Only then did I break down what I had agreed to. 

Nearly 2 marathons over 2 days whilst becoming more and more sleep deprived, having to get up in the early hours to go and run when I've never been a morning runner! I have historically completed ironman distance triathlons and mountain marathons, but at least these are completed within a day and in the daylight. This will be a physical and mental challenge like no other.

Now having seen the weather we will be running in subzero temperatures as well! 

My schedule will be:

  1. 8pm 5th March first run (forecast temperature 3C)
  2. 12am 6th March - Night run (forecast temperature 0C)
  3. 4am 6th March - Night run (forecast temperature -1C)
  4. 8am 6th March - Morning run (forecast temperature 0C)
  5. 12pm 6th March - Day run (forecast temperature 5C)
  6. 4pm 6th March - Day run (forecast temperature 5C)
  7. 8pm 6th March - Night run (forecast temperature 3C)
  8. 12am 7th March - Night run (forecast temperature 2C)
  9. 4am 7th March - Night run (forecast temperature 1C)
  10. 8am 7th March - Morning run (forecast temperature 3C)
  11. 12pm 7th March - Day run (forecast temperature 6C)
  12. 4pm 7th March - Day run (forecast temperature 7C)

The charity

Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.Thank you.

eventName: Walk a marathon in a day
story:
In 2010 the D-Class Inshore Lifeboat Ollie Naismith was officially named and went on service at Looe. The lifeboat was named after a popular local teenager Ollie Naismith who sadly died in a tragic road traffic accident in 2009. Ollies parents, Maxine and John Naismith spearheaded a fundraising campaign to raise the funds for the lifeboat which has gone on to save many lives in and around Looe including the life of Louis Webber, a young local lad who was of a similar age to Ollie. 

The lifeboat is now coming to the end of its operational life so the team at Looe Lifeboat station are teaming up with the Naismiths and Webber family to launch the Looe Lifeboat Appeal to raise the £78,000 required to provide a replacement lifeboat which will be named the Ollie Naismith II.

Your donation to this community appeal will help to fund this lifeboat which will continue the selfless work of our volunteer lifeboat crew in Looe.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. charity.name: Unicef UK
eventName: Alliance for Better Care supporting Unicef Covid Solidarity Fund
story:
Alliance for Better Care has now vaccinated over 100,000 patients across East Surrey and Mid-Sussex. As part of this milestone, we are calling on our team and patients to join us as we fundraise for the Unicef Childrens Covid Emergency Fund.

Unicef urgently need funds to expand the scale and scope of their work supporting children affected by coronavirus, especially in countries with weaker health systems.

£60 transports 4,205 doses of vaccines
£45 provides cold chain equipment to safely store 500 doses
of vaccine
£30 gives a full kit to protect a health worker, including
boots, gloves, masks and coveralls
£20 buys 781 pairs of gloves for health workers
£10 buys 56 bars of soap to help prevent the spread of the
disease
£5 provides 1,350 water purification tablets to purify water
in emergency situations

The impact of a large-scale outbreak of coronavirus on children, especially poor and vulnerable children, has been immense. Children are at risk from the disease, but also from the disruption to health and education services, impacts on caregivers, and separation from family members.

Unicef has been working closely with governments and the World Health Organization (WHO) since the start of the coronavirus outbreak. Donations made to our page will help to limit the spread of the virus and reduce the impact on children and families.

We want to ensure that we support people around the world
who don’t have sufficient funds to vaccinate their population or have the infrastructure to arrange a programme like we can in Surrey and Sussex.

We know that If we were to pay for the two doses of vaccine ourselves, it would cost between £5- £20 per person. If you would like to donate the equivalent of your vaccine, you can do that through us.

charity.name: Unicef UK
eventName: Give a Shot, Give a Jab
story:
If you have recently had your Covid vaccination or are due to have one soon, please 'pass it forward' - you got a shot,  so help give a shot, give a jab. 

Unicef is playing a crucial role in the Covid vaccination drive - to ensure all countries have access to safe and effective vaccines. Working alongside partners, including COVAX (the vaccine element), the World Health Organisation, Gavi the Global Vaccine Alliance, governments, health organisations and others, Unicef is already on the ground, procuring, distributing and administering approved vaccines into arms. 

In accordance with guidance from the World Health Organisation, health workers, alongside the most vulnerable, are being targeted in the first wave of vaccination, ensuring they can work in safety whilst helping to get essential and life-saving services back on track for some of the world's poorest communities. 

Only through ensuring that the world’s poorest countries have the same opportunity as richer countries in urgently vaccinating their health workers and vulnerable can we end the pandemic and its devastating impact on everyone.

No matter how small or how big your donation, it is so very much appreciated. Thank you for caring about the health of others around the world and helping urgently deliver the largest health and logisitics operation the world has ever seen.

In 2021, Unicef will deliver 2 billion vaccines, 245 million therapeutics and 500 million tests as well as support countries to prepare and deliver the world’s most extensive and fastest ever vaccination operation. Your donation helps do this!

If those in the UK who have already had their NHS vaccine donated just £1 each, to date, we could raise £20 million so please, please pass it forward #giveashot #giveajab 


One world, one love…with gratitude,
Aiysha xx


Why Unicef and Covax?
Unicef is equipped to match the enormity of this global operation - with a presence in over 190 countries, they already deliver nearly 2.5 billion doses of health vaccines annually to some of the hardest to reach places on the planet. Unicef has the knowledge and systems needed to succeed in ensuring all countries have equal access to the Covid vaccine.

As the largest vaccine buyer in the world, with a vast country presence and decades of experience in supplying and preparing countries and communities for immunisation programmes, UNICEF will play a critical role in the rollout of COVID 19 vaccines through COVAX, catalysing a global recovery. COVAX is the vaccines element of ACT-A. Led by Gavi, the Global Vaccine Alliance, the Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations (CEPI) and World Health Organisation (WHO), it aims to accelerate the development and manufacture of Covid-19 vaccines, and to guarantee fair and equitable access globally. 

Unicef is leading the procurement and supply of COVID-19 vaccines—as well as freight, logistics and storage—for 92 low-and middle-income countries, and a buffer stockpile for humanitarian emergencies. This will be supported by donor funds. UNICEF will also support procurement by 98 higher-income economies who will finance the vaccines from their own public finance budgets. In parallel, UNICEF is working to secure access to safe injection equipment and cold chain equipment, to support a rapid rollout of COVID-19 vaccines.

charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
THE CHALLENGE is to have collectively (BVK7 & BVK8) travelled around Planet Earth by Wednesday 31st March, a staggering 40,075km or ~52.5 million steps!

THE COMPETITION will be to see which team can raise the most money for our charities (UNICEF & The National Emergencies Trust) whilst doing so.

The MATHS
Over the last 55 days, our 127 active participants have collectively walked 33 million out of 52.5 million steps required - an average of 4.6k steps per participant per day. For us to ‘walk the world’ in 86 days with our current number of participants we would have to ↑ our ave. number of steps/participant by 400 to 5k per day!

Can we do it?

charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
As many of you will know I am a keen runner, so I thought why not put this to good use and try and raise some money for charity. 

To keep me motivated to cover as much distance as possible I will be asking people to pledge an amount based on how far I run. So for example 10p per a kilometre. Bare in mind I typically run somewhere around 200 km a month, so you have been warned! haha. 

If you want to just donate a one off payment, if that is easier for you. That would also be most welcome! 

I have linked my Strava profile to the page so everyone can keep up with the progress, I will also be giving weekly updates. 

I picked Unicef because of the food programs they are running in Yemen. Shortfalls in the foreign aid and the pandemic as a whole has left many people, particularly children facing one of the worst famines in recent history. Current estimates by the UN state that; 

"368,000 children under 5 are suffering from severe acute malnutrition and urgently need life-saving food to survive."

Thank you so much for your support and thank you for any donations you can make!

charity.description: Malaria No More UK mobilises governments, influencers, businesses and the public to end deaths from malaria and wipe out the disease for good. Our mission is to catalyse and inspire the global partnerships, leadership and financing to make malaria no more in a generation.
charity.name: MALARIA NO MORE UK
eventName: Every family sleeping in amosquitoe net
story: Every two minutes a child under 5 dies from malaria and yet, it is preventable and treatable. Since 2000 we’ve cut world malaria deaths by 60%, but that progress is in jeopardy and we need to step up efforts. By making a donation, you’ll be helping to protect children and their families from malaria, save lives and create a world where no child suffers needlessly. That means more kids in school, more people in work, less pressure on health services. A future with less poverty and more economic growth.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: WaterAid is working to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. The international not-for-profit organisation works in 28 countries to change the lives of the poorest and most marginalised people. Since 1981, WaterAid has reached 26.4 million people with clean water and 26.3 million people with decent toilets.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

story: Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.

charity.description: CARE International is one of the world’s leading aid agencies working in over 80 countries around the globe. We seek a world of hope, tolerance and social justice, with  women and girls at the centre, where poverty has been overcome, and people live with equal opportunities in security and dignity.
charity.name: CARE International UK
story:
This women's day Greenstone is raising donations for CARE International which is the leading NGO in women’s economic and social uplifting. 

Every £5 donation will also get you one ticket in our RAFFLE DRAW, the winner of which will receive a PRIZE! 

Greenstone will also match donations up to £50 per team member. 

Please make your donations through this page from Monday - Friday and the raffle winner will be announce at the Friday drinks. 

Thank you for your support! 

ABOUT CARE

CARE focuses on four interrelated pathways to women's economic empowerment and they contribute to the greatest impact: Dignified work, Financial inclusion, Women's entrepreneurship, Women in value chains. 

COVID has emphasized the need to make sure that women across the world are resilient in times of crisis and donations will go to supporting the most vulnerable. 

For more information see: https://www.careinternational.org.uk/

YOUR DONATION

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.
